What's the most insane coincidence that's happened to you? The day before my daughter was going into kindergarten, her father and I listened to the worst news of our lives. We spent the next six months in the hospital with her before she passed away. My husband and I split up shortly after, and I was alone for years. But one night after I got home from work, I sat on my back porch remembering how she used to play in our backyard. I noticed something stuck in a bush around the side of my house, and when I got closer, it was a pink balloon. I was just gonna throw it out, but saw it had a note taped to the side. I opened it and could see a message written in crayon. It was really hard to read, but it said, happy Birthday, Mommy. I miss you. Please send me a sign. Love, Callie. I was confused at first, but then I realized what it was. Whoever this little girl was had lost her mom and was sending her a message. I asked around my neighborhood later that week and found what house she lived at. I talked to her father and told him I found one of her balloons. He apologized and said she had been doing that for a while. She was 6 and lost her mom two years before. I told him about my daughter and how I would love to write back to her. Just in case it would cheer her up, I wrote her a note that said, hi, Kelly. I found your balloon. I miss you, and I'm watching over you every day. Love, mommy. The next night, he called me and told me she was so excited she sent another balloon up, and he asked if I could do it again. After a week, he asked me to meet her. And she was the sweetest girl I've ever met. Five years later, she's now my stepdaughter. But this morning, she said something I'll never forget. She told me she thinks she has two mommies. One up there and one who found her balloon.

My brother kicked me out over his wife's lies. Now they're homeless with kids and I refuse to let them back in my life. When I was 22, I inherited our grandmother's house, a beautiful Victorian with enough space for my brother and his family to stay while they saved for their own place. They moved in with their two kids, promising it would only be temporary. Just six months, my brother assured me, will be out of your hair before you know it. His wife despised me from day one. She'd make snide comments about how I decorated, complained that I was too loud when I came home from my nursing shifts and acted like I was invading her space in my own house. She'd rearrange my kitchen without asking, throw away my mail, claiming it was junk, and lecture me about proper household management while I was paying all the bills. The passive aggression escalated weekly. She'd use my expensive shampoo, then deny it when confronted. My leftovers would disappear from the fridge. She'd claim she thought they were communal food when I started labeling everything with my name. She complained to my brother that I was being petty and territorial. I tried talking to my brother about her behavior, but he always made excuses. She's stressed about money. She's not used to living with other people. You're being too sensitive. Every conversation ended with him defending her and dismissing my concerns. The breaking point came six months Later, I arrived home exhausted from a double shift to find her screaming at me in the hallway. She claimed I've been stealing money from her purse and eating her food from the fridge. Both accusations were ridiculous. I made decent money and kept my own groceries clearly labeled. You've been sneaking into our room. I freaked her face red with manufactured rage. I know you took $40 from my wallet last Tuesday. I stared at her in disbelief. I worked 12 hour shifts. When exactly would I have time to rifle through your belongings? Don't lie to me, she spat. I have proof. My brother stood behind her, silent as she launched into a tirade about how I was jealous of their family and trying to sabotage their marriage. When I tried to defend myself, she burst into tears and ran to their room. That night, my brother knocked on my door. His face was stone cold, a look I'd never seen directed at me before. We need to talk, he said. He told me his wife had been documenting everything. Times I allegedly took money, instances where I supposedly threatened her when he wasn't around, photos of missing food items. None of it was true, but he believed every word. She created a detailed log with dates, times and descriptions of my supposed crimes. You're toxic and you're tearing our family apart, he said. We're done enabling your behavior. I stared at him in disbelief. This was the Same brother who'd cry.

I lied to my wife that I'd forgive her cheating. So my wife, Emma, came home last Tuesday with that look on her face, the one all guilty and nervous like she just got caught stealing candy. She sat me down on our ratty old couch and started crying before she even said anything. Turns out she'd been hooking up with her coworker Jake for like three months. Three months while I was working double shifts at the warehouse to save up for our anniversary trip to Florida. She kept saying sorry over and over, begging me not to leave her, promising she'd cut all contact with this guy. I just sat there staring at our wedding photo on the coffee table, the one where we're both laughing because my cousin Rick photobombed us making bunny ears. We looked so happy, so stupid. Emma grabbed my hands and asked if I could ever forgive her. And here's where I became a complete psychopath. I looked her dead in the eyes and said yes. I told her we could work through this, that our marriage was stronger than one mistake, all that bullshit you see in movies. But I was lying through my teeth. The next morning, I called in sick to work and drove straight to Jake's apartment, found his address through Emma's Instagram. She tagged him at some restaurant last month. Dude answered the door in his boxers looking all confused. Introduce myself as Emma's husband and Watched his face go white. Then I very calmly explained that I knew everything and that he had exactly 24 hours to quit his job and move out of town or I'd be paying visits to his parents, his ex girlfriend Sarah, who he was apparently trying to win back, and his boss who definitely didn't know he was screwing around with married co workers. Jake started stuttering about how sorry he was, how it meant nothing. I just smiled and handed him a printed email I'd already drafted to his entire office explaining the situation, told him this would be sent if he wasn't gone by Thursday. Me while at home, I was being the perfect forgiveness husband, made Emma her favorite pasta dinner, bought her flowers, even suggested couple therapy. She was so relieved and grateful, telling me how lucky she was to have such an understanding husband. Thursday came and Jake was gone. Just like that, Emma came home from work all confused because apparently he'd quit without notice and moved back to Ohio or something. She kept asking why he just disappear like that. I waited exactly one more week, let her think we were rebuilding our trust. Then last Friday, I casually mentioned over breakfast that I changed my mind about the whole forgiveness thing. Her face went from confused to terrified in about two seconds. I told her I'd known.

My boyfriend's manipulative best friend weaseled into our romantic getaway and then spent the entire time trying to break us up. So I got the perfect revenge. She crashed our cabin weekend, claiming her Airbnb fell through. I knew it was BS. The moment she showed up with a perfectly packed bag and a smug smile. My boyfriend, Joseph, felt bad for her and invited her to stay without even asking me. For three days straight, she kept creating these elaborate situations to make me look like the worst girlfriend ever. Like when she helped make dinner on Friday night. She volunteered to preheat the oven while I prepped ingredients. Everything seemed normal until I put our carefully marinated steaks in and they came out completely charred. She acted shocked when Joseph got mad at me for ruining our expensive dinner. Later, I noticed she'd secretly cranked the oven to 500 degrees. Saturday morning, she suggested we go hiking to this amazing waterfall she'd been to before. She gave me detailed directions to the trailhead while she rode with Joseph. Turns out she sent me to the wrong trail entirely. I spent two hours lost in the woods with no cell service while they bonded over waiting for me. When I finally found them at the actual trailhead, Joseph was visibly annoyed I'd kept them waiting. She just shrugged and said, oh, I guess I mixed up the directions. My bad. The manipulation got worse as the weekend went on. She kept doing this thing where she'd bring up inside jokes and memories from before I existed, making, make me feel like an outsider in my own relationship. Remember when we did this and remember when we did that, always with this little smile directed at me. She'd also accidentally brush against Joseph, constantly grab his arm when laughing and find excuse is to lean over him. During Saturday afternoon, we decided to go swimming in the lake. She conveniently forgot to pack a swimsuit and asked to borrow one of mine. The one she picked was my smallest bikini and she made sure to comment loudly about how loose it was on her while adjusting it right in front of Joseph. Then she suggested we play volleyball in the water and kept accidentally bumping into me, making me lose my balance. The breaking point was Saturday night. We were all sitting by the fire when she pretended to be drunk and started crying about how much she missed the old days before I came along and changed everything. She was literally sobbing into Joseph's shoulder.

What's the fastest you've seen someone fired from a job? When I was 16, my dad told me I had to get a job or he'd kick me out of the house, and the only one I could find was at Build a bear. On my first day, I had to learn all the happy dances you do when a kid comes in, and after an hour of that, I was completely on my own. My manager left me there by myself, so I was really nervous. But I noticed a couple come in, and the woman was very pregnant. They didn't have a kid with them, but I still helped them pick out a bear along with a fancy heart that had a heartbeat. They still didn't look happy at all, so I tried to cheer her up and made the woman do the happy dance before I stuffed the bear for them. I could see they were both still really upset and not knowing what to do, I made the mistake of asking her if she was okay. She just looks up at me and told me they were there to make a bear for her baby be to be buried with, because they had just found out their baby's heart wasn't beating anymore. I immediately stopped trying to make her dance and could barely keep it together as I made the bear for her. It took everything I had to keep a smile as I helped them. Pay, but as soon as they left, I ran to the back and completely bawled my eyes out. My manager came back to the store a minute later, saw the huge line, and then found me crying in the back. I tried to explain what happened, but he just told me to get out because I was fired.

No, no one is calling you anything. I'm literally six foot tall. The chairs just don't pump most of my clients up high enough. I'm the tallest stylist in the salon, so my boss went ahead and got me a stool so that it would make things easier on me. Yeah, making things easier is something a lazy person would say. And I'm sure your co workers would love to sit down, too, because no one else is 6 foot tall. Okay, so elaborate. Tell me how exactly sitting down makes you more efficient as a stylist. Okay, well, in many different ways. For one, do you do great work whenever you're in pain? Like, if you go to work and you're sick, are you probably gonna get a lot done that day, or are you going to do the best that you can do? Probably not. I'd be too distracted by not feeling well. Okay, so same with me. This chair alleviates my pain, therefore making me a better stylist, because I can focus more on the hair in front of me rather than the back pain that I'm in from bending down for such a long amount of time. Also, when I'm bent over, I'm going downward. I'm bent downward, so the haircuts slant downward. This chair allows me to be level with your head so I can cut in a straight line. Oh, why didn't you just say so instead of calling me short? Okay, well, for The second time, no one called you anything, and you never asked. You just called me lazy. No need to get snippy. It was an innocent mistake. Can you just hurry up? Sure. Okay. And you're done. Let's go get you checked out. Okay. Um, can I come back in about 10 weeks? Great. I'll set you up with one of our stylist that stands while she cuts hair.

What if we go up to check out and I've done X amount of services and it costs X amount of money, and I tell them, and they get that sticker shock look in their eyes and they tell me that they can't afford it and that they don't have that much. Then you know what you do? I literally do not. Either they pay, or you're going to call the cops and report them for theft of services. Since you skipped all of that boring, time consuming talk about budget at the beginning of the appointment and instead went on to do any and all services that you deem necessary to give them the dream hair that they. Yes, they asked for. Services have now been rendered, and it is theft of services. And when they try to be like, but the price wasn't disclosed at the beginning, I didn't know it would be this much, or else I would have never done it. Blah, blah, blah, blah, you point at the price list that is on the front desk for all to see and remind them that our prices are listed online. Their negligence to check that they could afford it is not your problem. And I tell you what, most people find that. That they can't afford the services because they can't afford bail. Okay? So my mama definitely raised me to put in a two weeks and to be professional, but, yeah, I don't want my Name or my license attached to this. So this is my last day? Um, actually, it's my last minute. Goodbye. You need to tell your conscience that having one doesn't pay the bills.

I'm sorry, bear with me. Uh, you know, I am obviously not used to salon culture outside of anything other than beauty school, but isn't some money better than no money? Um, why would we not try to accommodate them based on what they can afford? Poor listening skills needs to be added to the list of things that you need to work on. Good to know. Anyway, as I was saying, it takes up too much time when you get to the beauty budget part of a consultation and someone says, Lo and behold, I can't afford that. They still want it though, right? And then you find yourself haggling with the client because they want more for less and you're trying to accommodate them for what? For less money and the same amount of work. No consultations are a lot more modern than they used to be and people are much more likely to ask how much it's going to cost beforehand. So what if someone brings it up? There's always a thorn in my side when people do ask. Obviously act accordingly then. But if someone doesn't do their due diligence of asking, then you get to do whatever you need to do, however many services you need to do to fulfill their expectation for that inspiration photo and at the end you charge accordingly. What if they can't afford it? They can afford it.

Answering anyone beyond one night of drinks? Tuesday, I had another idea. Melissa had been trying to become a lifestyle influencer, carefully curating her Instagram as successful and relationship oriented. Those Miami stories were still visible. She couldn't delete them without her phone. I screenshotted everything and forwarded them to every brand she tried partnering with over the past months. Professional emails explaining they should know what type of content this potential brand representative was posting. Wednesday, I discovered Melissa never established a legal tendency when she moved in. No lease, no contract. It was just a guest with no legal rights to my property. Thursday, her mother called. I explained everything and forwarded the screenshots. I can't say this surprises me. Karen said she pulled similar behaviour with her previous boyfriend. Turns out Melissa had an established pattern. Moving in with men with stable incomes, gradually stopping contributions while increasing spending, then searching for an upgrade. Friday, I finally answered one of her calls. Tyler, please. I'm stuck here with no money and nowhere to stay. I let her talk for 15 minutes, making increasingly desperate promises. Melissa, you called another man your sponsor while spending my money. You advertised yourself as single while living in my house rent free. We're finished. Figure it out yourself. Last week, those Miami stories have been screenshot and shared throughout our entire Social Circle. Brand partnerships rejected her. Her influencer dreams died. She posted a gofundme for $4,500, claiming financial abuse. It raised $12 before being removed. Thursday, she appeared at my workplace looking like she's been sleeping in her car. Designer clothes replaced with wrinkled jeans, no makeup, unwashed hair. I messed up lately. No one will hire me because those screenshots come up. I'm living in my car. Please help me start over. I looked at this woman who treated me like a human ATM while planning to replace me. You called another man your sponsor while I paid for your trip. Don't you believe in second chances? I believe in consequences. You wanted to be sponsored by someone else. You're free to pursue that without my money interfering. As I walked away, she sobbed, what am I supposed to do? Figure it out like an adult.

Single for this weekend. My girlfriend posted with a video of her making out with a stranger while her entitled friends cheered her on. I didn't get mad. I just pulled out my phone and did something that made her regret it. My girlfriend Melissa and I had been together almost 4 years. I work construction management in Phoenix making $125,000 annually. She moved into my house 18 months ago and gradually stopped contributing financially while spending hundreds weekly on lash extensions, nails, finer clothes and professional styling. For the past year, I'd covered everything, mortgage, utilities, groceries, her car insurance, even her phone Bill. Every time I question the disconnect, she'd cry about how her appearance was essential for career opportunities. Three weeks ago, Melissa and her friends planned a girls trip to Miami. By the time she left, I spent $3,400 on flights, hotel, spending money and new outfits. Friday evening, my best friend Jake called check Melissa's Instagram Stories immediately. The first story showed her at a rooftop bar, caption, single girls weekend, no boys allowed. The next showed her dancing with some guy, his hands all over her. Caption, when in Miami, anything goes. And a video of her kissing him while her friends cheered. But the final story destroyed me. Melissa on another man's lap in a VIP section with champagne bottles everywhere. Caption, new sponsor alert, upgrade time. She was advertising herself as available for financial support while I funded the entire trip. Saturday, Morning, Jake arrived with an action plan. I systematically dismantled everything, canceled her return flight, removed her from my phone plan, removed her from my car insurance, canceled her authorized user status on my credit cards, canceled every streaming service subscription and membership I've been paying for, changed every password, enabled two factor authentication, moved my money to accounts she couldn't access. Her phone would stop working within hours. Her credit cards would decline everywhere. Every convenience would simply disappear. Sunday evening, my landline rang. Melissa calling from the hotel front desk. I let it go to the answering machine. Nine minutes of desperate panic. Her phone stopped working, her credit cards declined and none of her friends would help. Turns out Mr VIP section wasn't interested in actually.

My belly can continuously secrete oil. As long as I eat enough, I can endlessly squirt oil from my navel. Soon, my husband had filled two whole barrels. The oil buyer praised the quality. He handed my husband a crisp $1,000. Before he could savor it, my oil well suddenly ran dry. This was a catastrophe for him. Panic! He dashed to the grill. He poured olive oil into the pan at once, frying meat until it was greasy and crisp. Then he shoved the pieces into my mouth. He kept me stuffed to force more oil out of me. The more he fed me, the finer the oil I produced. He grew ecstatic and soon had 100 full barrels. A helpless loss of control made me weep. Soaked unexpectedly in oil, the ropes that bound me slackened. I summoned all my strength and broke free. Seeing it work, I used oil to loosen other ties. Freed from restraints, I resolved to punish my tyrant husband. First, I corked my oil spout with a bottle cap. Then, in desperation, I shoved the leftover grilled meat into my mouth. My belly swelled instantly from the food. I gulped down the remaining olive oil. Maxed out and distended, I waited for my husband to return. He came back jubilant from selling the oil, worried about wasting my nearly bursting belly. That's when I released the oil jet. A geyser of oil knocked him off his feet. But that blast was only the Start now. I'll force him to eat only leafy greens and produce fruit. Nutrient rich juice. This green elixir can green deserts and revive barren land. Michael, make him turn the whole desert into a forest.

I worked at this small call center type place, and our manager was one of those people who thought unpaid overtime was just part of the job. Every single day, like clockwork, we'd finish our shift at 4:55 p m, log off our computers, and then he'd make us go to the meeting room for a team meeting. 20 minutes every day. And here's the thing. We weren't getting paid for it. When I started, I was the newest person on this 10 person team. Everyone else had been there way longer than me, so I just figured this was normal. First day, we all logged off, walked to the meeting room, and sat there until 5:15 p m. While the manager talked about daily metrics, call quality, random policy updates. Basically stuff he could have sent in an email. I did the math in my head and thought, okay, that's an extra two and a half hours every two weeks. Not terrible for just sitting and listening. Then my first paycheck came. I looked at my hours and saw exactly 80. That's it. No overtime, no extra two and a half hours, nothing. I thought maybe it was a mistake, so I asked this guy named Trevor who sat next to me. He just laughed and said, yeah, man, we don't get paid for those meetings. I asked around the rest of the team, and everyone confirmed the same thing. We were all just doing this for free because Nobody wanted to be the person who said no. That annoyed me more than it probably should have. Like, 20 minutes doesn't sound like much, but it adds up. And the principle of it bugged me. If I'm required to be there.

My wife cornered me and asked, when were you planning on telling me about your second family? I froze and dropped the coffee mug I was holding. What? Elise, what are you talking about? My confusion must have looked like guilt to her because her face turned from hurt to pure rage in seconds. Don't you dare play dumb with me, Michael! She screamed, her voice cracking. I, I know about Bertha. I know about your son. I genuinely thought she was having some kind of breakdown. Elise, Honey, I don't know any Bertha. I don't have another family. Where is this coming from? I reached for her, but she yanked away like I was contaminated. Still lying even now. Her phone flew past my head and shattered against the wall. Elise, please. I swear on our children's lives, I have no idea what you're talking about. She pulled out her laptop, slamming it on the counter so hard I thought the screen would crack. A woman named Bertha contacted me on Facebook this morning. I know she's your girlfriend, Michael, and she's the mother of your one year old son, Dylan. Her fingers shook as she opened the messages. There it was. Photos of a baby boy with dark hair, messages detailing an affair, even a birth certificate with my name listed as the father. She says you've been seeing her for two years, that you met at that conference in LA, that you promised to leave me once. The kids started kindergarten. My mind raced trying to process this insanity. Elise, I've never been to LA. That conference was in Dallas. And you called me every night. She sent me 30 pieces of evidence, Michael. 30. Are you seriously telling me that Bertha is lying? Wait. Bertha? My brain exploded when I finally realized that I knew that name. Bertha was my new coworker who'd been aggressively flirting with me for three months. The same woman who I'd reported to HR just last week for inappropriate advances. Elise, that's my coworker. The one I told you about, who wouldn't leave me alone. I screamed, trying to save my marriage, but Elise was beyond listening, already grabbing her keys and purse. She knew about your birthmark, Michael. The one on your hip. How would she know that? I felt sick, realizing Bertha must have seen it when she accidentally walked into the men's locker room at the company gym. The reason for why I reported her. I'm going to my mother's. My lawyer will contact you. The door slammed so hard, the picture frames rattled.

My brother in law looked across the Thanksgiving table and asked my husband, is the baby feeling better? I paused with my fork halfway to my mouth, scanning the faces around me. Everyone else kept eating like this was completely normal conversation. My husband's sister was cutting her son's Turkey while my mother in law stirred gravy, both acting like someone had just asked about the weather instead of a baby that didn't exist. What baby? I laughed nervously, waiting for someone to explain the joke. The entire table went silent. My husband's face turned the color of ash and his wine glass started trembling in his grip. His brother glanced between us, suddenly realizing he'd stepped on a landmine. Your baby, he said, slowly, uncertainty creeping into his voice. The one with the fever last week when he called me about going to the emergency room. My husband shot to his feet so fast his air nearly tipped backward. We should talk privately, he whispered, voice cracking on the last word. But his brother kept talking, confused by the reaction. The baby you guys have been raising, I thought she was feeling better after that scare. I felt the blood drain from my face. We don't have a baby, I said, each word feeling like broken glass in my mouth. His brother's eyes went wide with horror as he realized what he just done. He turned to his brother. But you told me about her ear infection last month. You showed me videos of her walking. The room was spinning now. My mother in law dropped her serving spoon with a clatter. Walking, I whispered. There's a baby who can walk. My husband's hands were shaking violently. Now I can explain, he started, but his brother was already pulling out his phone. You showed me this video last week, he said, holding up the screen. A beautiful baby girl with my husband's eyes was taking bobbly steps across someone's living room. A woman's voice in the background was cheering her on. I recognized that voice, Rebecca, from his office, who'd eaten potato salad in my backyard last July while complaining about her divorce. That's Rebecca's apartment, I said, my voice eerily calm. I recognized the curtains from her Instagram. The truth crashed over me in waves. How old is she? I asked, though I already knew the answer would destroy me. 14 months, his brother said quietly, looking like he wanted to disappear. He said, you guys had her 14 months ago. I did the math instantly. While the room tilted sideways. That meant he'd gotten Rebecca pregnant. While I was researching fertility clinics and taking prenatal vitamins, I was timing intercourse with ovulation strips and lying with my legs elevated for 30 minutes afterward, desperate for the baby I thought we both wanted. You told him we had a baby together, I asked, turning to face my husband. You've been pretending our baby exists while raising one with Someone else, his mother gasped, putting her hand over her mouth.

At my football game, a cheerleader grabbed me and said, can you help me? It's coming. What's coming? I asked, setting down my water bottle on the bench. She was gripping my Jersey with one hand and holding her stomach with the other. Her face twisted in a way that made me think she was about to throw up. I thought she needed help with her skirt or something. But then she screamed at me more like all the air being forced out of her lungs at once. Suddenly, she collapsed behind our bench holding her stomach. And I started looking for her boyfriend. She was dating Owen, our starting quarterback, and they've been together since sophomore year. Help me, please get someone, she asked. And I'd never run so fast in my life. I didn't know who to get. I couldn't see a single girl in sight. So I grabbed the next best person. Our coach took one look at Jenna and his eyes went wide under the stadium lights. And I kept saying, it's too early. It's not supposed to happen yet, which didn't make any sense because what was too early? Our coach started freaking out. Before telling me to stay with Jenna, he went and grabbed one of our teachers, Missus Pruitt, from the stands. And as I kneeled next to her, I asked what was wrong. She was holding her stomach. And then it hit me. Jenna was having a baby right here during homecoming. The crowd was starting to notice something was wrong because we'd formed this weird huddle behind the bench. The referees were blowing their whistles, wondering why half our team wasn't on the field. Owen came jogging over in his quarterback year, asking what was wrong with his girlfriend. And Jenna grabbed my hand so hard, I thought she'd break it. Don't let him see. You can't let him see the baby, she whispered to me. But Owen was already trying to get there. Everyone in the stands were freaking out over what was happening. Every student was trying to see what was going on. The cheerleading squad had formed this protective circle around Jenna, but you could still hear her screaming over the marching band that was trying to play through their halftime show. We need to get her to the ambulance, Miss. This is Pruitt said. But when two players tried to lift Jenna, she screamed so loud, the referees actually stopped the game completely. No, the baby's coming now, Jenna yelled. And I swear you could hear every single person in that stadium gasp at the exact same time. Nobody knew Jenna was pregnant. She'd been doing backflips at last week's game. Owen heard and I saw him go from confused.

What's that school rule you hated the most? My school had this insane zero tolerance policy where any disrespect meant automatic suspension. I thought it was ridiculous until it destroyed the vice principal who created it. It was state testing week and our vice principal, Mrs. Chen, was on a power trip. She'd already suspended six kids that month for aggressive walking and intimidating posture. She lived to make examples of students. During lunch, my friend Marcus accidentally knocked over a water bottle. It rolled towards Chen's feet. She grabbed the school microphone. Who threw this at me? Marcus raised his hand. Sorry, Mrs. Chen. It just fell. Assault on staff. Three day suspension. The cafeteria went silent. 400 kids daring. Ma'am, I literally just talk. Looking back, make it five days. Marcus's little sister Emma started crying. She was only a freshman. Please, our parents will. Are you threatening me? Chen pointed at Emma. You're suspended too. That's when something snapped in the cafeteria. Jake stood up. This is insane. Suspended. Maria stood up. You can't do this. Suspended. Then 10 kids stood. 2050. Chen was screaming into the microphone. Everyone standing is suspended. Sit down now. Nobody sat. 400 students on their feet. Fine. Every single one of you suspended. Security, lock the doors. Security guards looked confused but obeyed. Chen started writing names frantically. Nobody leaves until I have every name for suspension letters. Three hours she kept just there. Three hours. Kids recording everything on their Phones. Chen didn't care. Record away. You're all suspended anyway. Sarah had a panic attack. Chen refused to let the nurse in. She's faking for sympathy. Tom, who was diabetic, needed his insulin from his locker. Not my problem. Should have thought about that before standing up. The basketball team was missing their championship game. Chen laughed. Actions have consequences. Parents were gathering outside, pounding on doors. Chen had security tell them it was a mandatory safety drill. But here's what Chen didn't know. Emma and Marcus, their dad was the state it's attorney General. And Sarah having the panic attack. Her mom was the biggest education lawyer in the state. Tom's parents ran the local news station. By five PM, when Chen finally opened the doors, the parking lot looked like a crime scene. News vans, police, police cars, the superintendent, the mayor, parents with lawyers. Chen walked out confident. Your children were suspended for assault and insubordination. Letters will be mailed. The attorney general stepped forward with a stack of papers. Mrs. Chen, you're being charged with false imprisonment of 400 minors, child endangerment and denial of medical care. Chen laughed. I'm authorized.

I borrowed my husband from the bedroom tonight. So. I'm a nurse. I work about 50 hours a week in pediatric ICU, which is exactly as soul crushing as it sounds. I cry at least once a week because watching sick kids struggle is brutal, and there's only so much you can take before it breaks you a little. My paycheck covers everything. Rent, groceries, utilities, insurance, everything. Every single Bill gets paid because I show up and do my job. My husband is 25. He has a degree he's not using and works two days a week at a grocery store. The rest of his time goes to league of legends. That's it. Just him and his computer. And his best friend, who also doesn't work. We've been married for a year and a half, and we haven't had a single Saturday off together since our wedding day. Not one. I've been begging him for weeks to swap his Saturday shift to literally any other day so we could finally spend a weekend together like normal couples do. He finally agreed. Today was supposed to be that day. I had it all planned out. We were going to this animal sanctuary about 40 minutes away that I've been wanting to visit forever. I was so excited, I could barely sleep the night before. I woke up around 9 and he was already gone. No note, no text. I called him. He was at breakfast with his best friend. Said They were just catching up and then he was going to help him set up some lights at his place. Oh, and also the weather was too rainy for the animal sanctuary anyway, so we should probably just skip it. I looked outside. It was drizzling. Not even real rain, just that annoying mist that doesn't actually stop you from doing anything. He got home around 1 in the afternoon. Didn't apologize, didn't acknowledge that he ditched our plans. Just flopped on the couch and turned on his game. I asked if we were still cooking dinner together like he promised, and he said yeah. Yeah, of course, babe. Just let me finish this match. At 5. He left again. Same friend needed help with something else. I didn't even ask what, because at that point I didn't care. I needed groceries, so I walked to the store. I don't drive because of some medical stuff, so walking is just what I do. It started raining harder while I was there. Not drizzling anymore, actual rain. I bought everything we needed and walked back in the cold and the wet.

At my brother's baby shower, my mom raised a framed deed. A gift from all of us. I looked closer. It was the apartment I'd paid off in full. My dad leaned in. You have 30 days to VAC, Kate. I smiled. One day is enough. By sunrise, the locks were changed. By noon, everything they'd moved in was gone. The flooring they installed, the crib. They bought that ridiculous wall decal that said, our little nest. All of it boxed up and removed. That evening, my brother texted, is this a joke? I replied, not yet, but tomorrow's delivery might be. I bought that apartment in 2020. Small, quiet, walking distance from work. Mine. My brother showed up with his girlfriend two years later. Just until we find something. One month, maybe two. They stayed 19. I never asked for rent. They promised groceries sometimes. Most of the time, they forgot. I figured it was temporary. It wasn't. First came the floating floors. My brother said it was an upgrade for everyone. Then the bookshelf. His girlfriend posted photos with captions like, our place is coming together. I was literally standing behind the camera. Slowly, their language changed. Your apartment became our space. Their toothbrushes appeared in my cup, their shoes by the door. I never said anything. Then came the baby. I found out through Instagram. Her holding a sonogram, him flexing. He texted me, we should talk about making things more permanent. I said, no. Three weeks, Later, my mom called. They're starting a family. You're doing well. Can't you just gift them the apartment? I hung up. Here's the thing. Over four years, I paid over $200,000 into that apartment. Mortgage, taxes, repairs, utilities, furniture. I covered my parents mortgage when my dad was recovering, my sister's rent when she was between jobs, my uncle's legal fees, emergency dental work for my mom. I kept track of none of it because I thought family meant something. My brother contributed $900 for the floor, one bookshelf, a used blender. When I refused to hand over the deed, they didn't argue. They tried to reassign the property title with a forged signature, used a scan from an old tax form. And reassigned the property title without my consent. At the baby shower, they acted like they were doing me a favor. Like I should clap and smile and feel included in their generosity. A gift from all of us, my mom said.
NA

That teenager who shoved her friend off a 60 foot high bridge will spend as much time in jail as her friend spent in the hospital. Attorneys thought they'd worked out a plea deal to keep the young woman out of jail, but the judge had another idea. Punishment for the teen who pushed her friend off a bridge. Nineteen year old Taylor Smith was in tears as she was escorted away in handcuffs after being sentenced to two days in jail. The ruling surprised both sides. Taylor had pled guilty to reckless endangerment and prosecutors recommended no jail time, but the judge refused to go along. Jordan plunged 60 feet into the water, landing chest first. She suffered six broken ribs and punctured lungs. At the sentencing, Taylor said she was sorry, then off she went to jail for two days. Jordan says she's ready to move on. I think it's probably just as emotional for her as as me. I'm happy it's over. Taylor Smith was also ordered to spend 38 days on a work crew.

Well, that couple took matters into their own hands. And built A large dirt berm, as you can see, around their home. The homeowner tell me, tells me it was pretty expensive to build, and they're not even sure if it's going to work. But they say after all they've been through, they had to try something. This was Pam and Mark Teters home after Hurricane Milton. The couple had only just moved from North Carolina three months before. And while the flooding from Milton is long gone, the teters still have standing water on parts of their property. From rainstorms that happened after. It's tearing up their lives. Pam approached the county several times for help, even offering a few suggestions, like building A berm around the retention pond next door, or digging their ditches. And that we were the lowest point in this area, and that all the water would. Would flow to us. That's when they decided to take tens of thousands of dollars out of their savings to build their own burn. It was our last option. We talked to several contractors, and they suggested that we do that.

Got text from dad. Family meeting tomorrow, two PM. Important inheritance discussion. I was refinishing an antique dresser when my phone buzzed. My dad. We barely talk. Maybe once every few months. Family meeting tomorrow. Two PM. Important inheritance discussion. About Grandpa Orlando's estate. Be there. No. Hello? No. How are you? Just that my grandpa passed three weeks ago. He was 84. The only person in my family who ever got me. Amazing craftsman who restored historical buildings. Taught me everything about woodworking. Everyone else thinks what I do is a joke. My dad builds cookie cutter suburban developments and makes bank. My brother Kyler followed his path. Fancy SUVs, massive houses. I rent a modest apartment and drive a 2,011 Subaru that barely starts. I canceled my afternoon appointment, losing $300, and drove two hours to their Mcmansion. Pulled up at 1:55, right on time. Walking to the door, I heard loud laughter inside. Weird for an inheritance meeting. I knocked. No answer. Let myself in. There they all were. Dad, Mom, and Kyler around the dining table with wine glasses, fancy cheese plates and official papers. All dressed up like it's a Celebration. Dad looked up with this smirk. Oh, you actually came? We already divided everything about an hour ago. I stood there frozen. You said two. It's 1:58. Mom couldn't stop giggling. The 28 year old failure actually thought he was getting something. Kyler waved papers. We signed everything an hour ago. You get nothing. I'm still standing there, jacket half off, completely blindsided. What the hell is going on

I lost weight before my sister's wedding. My family acts like I committed a crime or something. Look, I was overweight my whole life. Like, really overweight. I'm talking about the kind where you avoid cameras at family events and people always feel the need to comment on what you're eating. For years I tried every diet you can think of. Nothing stuck. Then about a year and a half ago, something just clicked. I started walking more, stopped eating junk every night, drank actual water instead of soda. Normal stuff. The weight started coming off slowly at first, then faster. I lost around 90 pounds total. Here's the thing, though. I live like six hours away from my family, we don't really text much, and I barely use Instagram or anything, so they had no idea what I looked like now. I mentioned once or twice that I was eating better, but that's it. Honestly, I didn't want to make a big deal about it because every other time I tried losing weight, I failed. I didn't need my mom asking me every week how it was going or my aunt making comments at Thanksgiving. My sister got engaged last year. I was genuinely happy for her. She's marrying this guy who's actually pretty cool, and they seem good together. The wedding got delayed a few times because of venue issues or something. What? Ended up being scheduled for early this month since I haven't seen everyone in forever. I figured I'd come home two weeks early to help with wedding stuff and just hang out. I showed up at my parents house on a Tuesday afternoon. My mom opened the door and her jaw literally dropped. She just stared at me for like 10 seconds before yelling for my dad. He came over, looked confused, then said, oh, wow, honey, you look so different. It was awkward, but fine. Then my sister walked in from the kitchen. She stopped dead in her tracks. Her face went from confused to angry in about two seconds. She didn't say hi, she didn't hug me. She just goes, are you serious right now? I had no idea what she meant. I asked her what was wrong, and she said, you couldn't have waited until after my wedding to do this? I still didn't get it. I asked her to explain and she literally shouted, you lost all this weight right before my wedding to make me look bad. I was so confused. I told her I've been losing weight for over a year and it had nothing to do with her wedding. She wasn't hearing it. She said I was trying to steal attention and make her feel fat. For the record, my sister looks completely fine. She's gained maybe 15 or 20 pounds since she got engaged, but it's not even that noticeable. She still looks like herself. But apparently this is the first time in our entire lives that I've weighed less than her, and she couldn't handle it. My parents immediately jumped in on her side. My mom said I should have warned them that I looked so different. My dad said it was inconsiderate timing. I tried explaining again that I didn't plan this around her wedding. I didn't even know she'd gained weight. But my sister started crying, saying I was ruining everything and that everyone at the wedding would compare us. She said people would whisper about how the bride's sister looked better.

My boss fired me after finding out I had a job interview during my vacation day despite bringing in $2 million in new business and getting denied a raise three times. This shows you're not committed to our team, he said, demanding I clean out my desk immediately. I thanked him for the opportunity and left calmly. Monday would be fun. Lawrence Bennett leaned back in his custom leather chair, tan from his Miami business trip. Four years at Dryfield Robotics, four years watching Tyler Davis get promoted over me despite my numbers being double his. And Tyler took credit for the Westbrook deal I'd spent six months building. Then he got a company car. Meeting invites started missing my inbox, little comments in meetings. Are you sure that's the right approach? Last month, I closed Abbott Manufacturing, $2 million, our biggest contract of the year. I flew to Chicago three times on my own dime, worked every weekend, missed my cousin's wedding. When the contract came through, Lawrence took the, came out for drinks, everyone except me. I found out from Instagram. That's when I asked about my raise. Third time asking, the timing isn't right. Lawrence said, we're restructuring compensation. That night, I updated my resume for the first time in four years. A week later, Vanessa Mills reached out on LinkedIn, former dry field client, now at Ravi. On publishing over coffee, she mentioned they needed someone to head their business development division, someone like me. I took one Vacation day for an interview. Someone saw me in the Ravion lobby and told Tyler. Now, Lawrence sat across from me waiting for me to beg. I understand, I said. His eyebrows twitched. You're terminated effective immediately. Clean out your desk. I stood up and extended my hand. He hesitated before taking it. Thank you for the opportunity. The walk back was quiet. Everyone pretending to be busy, stealing glances. I pulled a cardboard box from the supply room, a coffee mug, some pens, a cactus I'd kept alive for three years, four years of my life, smaller than a microwave. April hovered nearby watching me like I might steal a stapler. I brought in $2 million. They thought I might steal office supply eyes. Tyler stepped out as I headed to the elevator, the man who'd assured me my raise was in process. He didn't make eye contact. Turn in your badge at security. In the elevator, I caught my reflection. I didn't look fired. I looked. Later. I sat in my car for an hour staring at the building where I'd spent four years believing loyalty meant something. My phone buzz. Text from Tyler, sorry about how things went down. I delete, needed it. Then another message. Email from Vanessa, can you come in tomorrow 10:00am? The team would like to meet you. I replied, yes. That night my father said they did you a favor. They showed you exactly who they are. He was right. The raviyon interview. Took 20 minutes. They'd already checked my references, already talked to Abbott Manufacturing. We want you as regional director. Vanessa said, double your dry field salary.

Fucking thing happened at a wedding that made everyone freeze up at once. Everyone knew Blake and Rosalie were going to last forever. Our girlfriends would literally use him as an example during every argument. This is what a real man looks like. He organized flash mobs for her birthday, Learned to cook her grandmother's recipes, and treated Rosalie like it was her birthday every day. Then Rosalie's mom got diagnosed with Lupus, and Blake didn't even hesitate. He switched to night shifts at his accounting firm so he could drive her mom to treatments during the day. He even sold his beloved motorcycle, the one he'd rebuilt with his dad, just to cover the copays when Rosalie's family hit their insurance limit. While the rest of us were complaining about meeting our girlfriend's parents once a month, Blake was at every single family dinner, helping Rosalie's mother cook, helping her dad fix the roof, and teaching her little brother to drive. Three years in, Blake proposed. He got down on one knee at her favourite restaurant with her whole family there. With her grandmother's ring he'd personally restored and gave this Speech about how she saved him from being a workaholic with no purpose. Whole restaurant started clapping. Rosalie was crying so hard she could barely say yes. The wedding planning was insane. Blake handled everything. She got stressed about vendor calls, seating arrangements, dealing with her crazy aunt who demanded vegan options for everyone. The day finally came. It was a beautiful beach and packed with 300 guests. Rosalie looked incredible walking down that aisle, her dad tearing up next to her. And Blake standing at the altar with tears already running down his face. The efficient Blake's best friend went through all the traditional stuff, the readings, the vows. Rosalie went first, and by the end, everyone was dabbing their eyes with juice. Then came the big moment. Do you, Blake, take Rosalie to be your lawfully wedded wife? The whole beach was silent. Everyone waiting for that enthusiastic yes we all expected. Blake looked at Rosalie for what felt like forever. Then he took a deep breath and said, clear as day, two hours ago, I would have hoisted you up in the air and screamed yes! But now you disgust me and I never wanna see you again in my life. He turned and walked away. Rosalie's face went from confused to horrified in about two seconds. She literally collapsed right there in her wedding dress. The best friend stood there with his mouth open. Blake's mom started running after him, screaming his name. Rosalie's bridesmaids rushed To her, trying to get her to breathe. The whole beach erupted. People were standing up, shouting, asking what the hell just happened. Blake just kept walking, got to the car park where a cab was waiting for him, and drove off. Nobody could make his. Groomsmen were blowing up his phone, getting nothing. Rosalie had to be sedated and taken to the hospital. Her brother started calling hospitals, thinking Blake had a psychotic break. Then Blake's best man, Tony, finally got through to him that night. What he found out made everyone's anger turn to complete shock. That morning, Blake had logged into his old Hotmail account from high school. He was looking for the first email he'd ever sent Rosalie, asking her to meet for coffee. He wanted to quote it in his vows, to show how far they'd come from that nervous kid asking her out. But in that old inbox, buried between spam

voice_to_text: Have you guys seen that girl who's gone viral for cleaning graves? At first, it looked pretty harmless. She was just scrubbing old headstones, showing the names, kind of like honoring people who've been forgotten. But then things started to get different. She began leaving flowers for complete strangers, which was sweet. But the real shocker when she found a child's grave with dolls or stuffed animals. She actually took them home, washed them until they looked brand new, and then brought them back to the cemetery. That's when people started questioning if she was crossing some sort of line. And ever since she's been doing this, weird things keep showing up in her videos. Like one night, she's filming while cleaning a grave, and out of nowhere, a flower just falls right out of the vase. Another time, she left her shovel on the ground, and it moved on its own. No wind, no reason. It just shifted. Now her followers are begging her to stop, warning that she might be attracting something dark, maybe even dangerous, by spending so much time with the dead and handling their things. But at the same time, others say she's just showing respect in her own way. So here's the real question. Is she doing something beautiful, or is she playing with fire? Let me know what you think in the comments.

My boss made a rule that he instantly regretted. Tuesday, our entire system crashed with 12 investors sitting in our conference room. I looked at the clock, saved my work, and started packing my bag. My boss, Steven ran in and I could smell the panic sweat on him. He screamed, fix this now! I felt completely calm as I showed him the email he'd sent Friday no overtime for any reason. I leave in 30 minutes. His face went from red to white so fast I thought he might faint. This disaster started three days ago when Steven called an all hands meeting. Corporate had cut overtime to save money, and Steven was practically glowing with excitement. He thought he'd look like a budget hero. I'd warned him our backup system died Thursday and the main system was failing. Our biggest client presentation was Tuesday. He'd said, do it during normal hours. I'd asked for the policy and writing, hoping he'd realize how stupid this was. Instead, he sent it to everyone, including corporate HR, adding that violations meant termination. HR confirmed it. I knew exactly what would happen and felt this weird mix of dread and satisfaction. Monday should have been Steven's warning. At three PM, the system started dying. The entire office was complaining. I called Steven and told him it needed two hours to fix. He asked, can you finish by 5? When I said no, he told me to handle it tomorrow. I felt my Jaw clench, but documented his response and sent it to HR for confirmation. They replied that I should follow my manager's directive with no exceptions to the overtime policy. Tuesday morning, the system was barely alive. Steven walked past my desk, repeat, each time looking more nervous. I could see him sweating through his shirt. He knew what was coming, but his pride wouldn't let him change the policy. At 4 p m, I sent him one final email saying the system would fail within an hour and needed three hours for repairs. I was giving him one last chance. He replied denied. Handle it tomorrow. My heart was actually racing because I knew what was about to happen. At 4:30 p m, everything died. The presentation, the client database. Three years

Just for this? To witness her exposing me? Sarah's eyes were red and puffy, the kind of crying that comes after practicing in front of a mirror. When I walked in, she immediately pointed at me. There she is. I want her to confess. Ask before I call the police. What exactly am I supposed to have done? I asked, setting down my laptop bag. Sarah launched into a dramatic monologue about trust and betrayal. According to her version, she'd spotted me wearing her necklace last weekend at Brianna's party. She claimed I must have picked the lock on her jewelry box, hole in it, and then been stupid enough to wear it in public. That's weird, I said calmly when she finally paused for breath. Especially since I was in Chicago visiting my sister last week, and I wasn't even at Brianna's party. You're lying! Sarah snapped. Fresh tears. Perfectly timed. Brianna, tell her you saw her there. Brianna looked uncomfortable. I mean, I thought I saw you, but it was pretty dark, and I had a few drinks. Check my Instagram, I suggested. I posted stories from Chicago all weekend. Sarah's face twitched slightly, but she recovered quickly. You could have scheduled those posts. The point is, my necklace is gone, and multiple people saw you wearing something that looked exactly like it. I could feel everyone watching me, waiting for my response. Our landlord, Mr. Collins, looked pretty particularly uncomfortable. Probably wondering how quickly he could end His lease with both of us, actually, I said, pulling out my phone. I installed security cameras after my car got broken into a few months ago. The color drained from Sarah's face so quickly, I thought she might.

How did someone fail miserably at trying to outsmart you? Sarah and I had been roommates for almost two years. We weren't best friends, but we tolerated each other well enough until I got promoted at the marketing firm where we both worked. The position she'd been eyeing for months went to me instead. And that's when everything changed. At first, it was just little things. My leftovers would mysteriously disappear from the fridge. My mail would end up accidentally in the trash. She'd have loud phone conversation is at 6 a m. Right outside my bedroom door. Annoying, but nothing I couldn't handle. Then her supposedly priceless family heirloom necklace went missing. This wasn't just any necklace. It was a white gold pendant with an emerald stone that she never shut up about. She'd tell anyone who would listen. I'd only seen her wear it twice in two years. I was working late on a Thursday when my phone exploded with texts from our mutual friends asking what I'd done. Confused, I called our other roommate, Jess. Dude, Sarah is losing it, Jess whispered. She's called the landlord, her parents, and like everyone we know, she's saying you stole her grandmother's necklace, and she has proof. What Sarah didn't know was that after my car was broken into three months earlier, I'd installed small security cameras throughout our apartment. Nothing fancy, just basic motion activated cams that uploaded to cloud storage. I hadn't even told my roommates about them. Because honestly, I'd nearly forgotten they were there. When I got home, I found our apartment had become some kind of amateur detective headquarters. Sarah had invited our landlord, four mutual friends and even her brother, who mysteriously drove two hours.

My vegan roommate kept insulting me for eating meat, so I bought carnivorous plants and place them next to hers. I'd lived with Amanda for three years in our two bedroom apartment. She was vegan since 14, had plants everywhere, and we never had issues. I ate my steaks, I made her quinoa bowls. Life was balanced. Amanda was obsessed with her plants. 47 different species across our apartment. Succulents on window sills, ferns hanging from ceilings, some tropical thing in a humidity tent. She named them all. If you bumped one, you got a death stare that could wilt the plants themselves. Then two months ago, Amanda went to an animal rights conference, came back a different person. Suddenly attending rallies every weekend, wearing aggressive vegan shirts, posting constantly on social media. I came home one Thursday with leftover steak. Amanda walked in and lost it. 10 minute rant about animal suffering. How could I look at myself? Eat meat? Made me a bad person. I tried laughing it off. We'd always respected each other's choices. She said that was before she saw the light and couldn't stay silent while I participated in murder. This became daily. Every time she saw me eating non vegan food, she'd make comments. Enjoying your corpse? Or that chicken had a family. It got so bad, I started eating bread first in my car at 5:00am. My coworkers thought I was insane. Why are you eating oatmeal in the parking lot? Because my Roommate became the vegan police. That's why. Three weeks of this. Finally, I told her, if this continues, I'm moving out. She crossed her arms. Good. I'll be glad when I don't have to live with an animal murderer. That's when creative inspiration hit. I mentioned her avocados probably killed more beings through monoculture than my eggs. She exploded, saying I didn't appreciate her efforts to save the planet. We were done. Least ended in two months. But I wasn't leaving quietly. Next day, while she was at a rally, I drove to an exotic plant store 20 minutes away. Asked the owner, what's the most dramatic carnivorous plant you have?

I'm already planning my speech about how her irrational fears almost cost her this opportunity. Floor 10, 11, 12. The building is beautiful, all glass and steel. I can see the city spreading out below. Then at floor 15, there's this sound like metal grinding against. The elevator suddenly lurches to the left, slamming me against the wall. The lights flicker once, twice, and go out completely. I'm in total darkness when the grinding sound gets louder, like something is literally tearing apart above my head. Floor 16, the elevator stops moving entirely. I can hear these awful snapping sounds echoing down the shaft, and the whole car drops three feet straight down before something catches it with a bone jarring crash. I'm thrown to the floor, my phone flying across the small space. The emergency phone is dead. The buttons don't work. I can hear my own heartbeat in the silence. Every few minutes, the elevator would drop another few inches as whatever was holding it up slowly gave way. I spent the next four hours trapped in that metal box, listening to cables snap one by one above me. The fire department had to cut through the shaft wall to get me out. The fire chief explained that the main support cable had been developing stress fractures for weeks. Invisible micro tears that their safety inspections couldn't detect. You're lucky, he said. If this had happened during rush hour with a full car, we'd be looking at multiple Fatalities. Christie was waiting in the lobby when they finally extracted me, still in her interview outfit. Mascara streaked down her cheeks. How did you know? I asked, my voice shaky from the adrenaline crash. She took a deep breath. My dad was an elevator technician for 30 years. I grew up in his repair shop, sleeping under workbenches while he fixed motors and cables. When I was little, he'd play this game where he'd make me close my eyes and listen to different elevators. Healthy ones versus ones that needed maintenance. I Learned to hear

My girlfriend Christie claims she can feel when elevators are broken before they actually break. For the past two years, I've watched her do this weird ritual at every elevator bank. She'll walk up to each one, press her ear against the door, and sometimes straight up refuse to get on. Always with some excuse about bad vibrations or something feeling off. Last month at the mall, she made us wait 20 minutes for a different elevator because the first one sounded wrong when she rejected. Worked perfectly fine all day. I started calling her the Elevator Whisperer as a joke, but honestly, it was getting embarrassing. The worst part was how she'd get this serious, almost scared look on her face when she'd reject one, like she was genuinely terrified of something the rest of us couldn't see or hear. Last Thursday, we're running late for her dream job interview at this prestigious law firm downtown. 22nd floor of this gorgeous glass building she'd been preparing for weeks. We rush into the lobby, and there's three elevators. Two have long lines of business people checking their phones. The middle one is completely empty, doors wide open, practically begging us to hop in. Christie freezes at the elevator bank, tilting her head like she's listening to something. Not that one, she whispers, pointing at the empty elevator. Her face has gone completely pale. I check my watch. We're already 15 minutes late. Christie, seriously? Today of all days? She backs Away from the middle elevator, shaking her head I can hear it in the motor. Something's grinding that shouldn't be grinding. The cable sound loose? The other two elevators are packed with people, and there's at least a 10 minute wait. Her interview is in five minutes. This. This is ridiculous! I snap. There's nothing wrong with it. Look, it's working fine! I gesture at the perfectly normal looking elevator. Please don't, she begs, grabbing my arm. I'm telling you, something is seriously wrong with that one. But I'm done with her elevator paranoia ruining important moments. Take off her hand and step into the empty elevator, hitting the button for 22. See you upstairs! I call out sarcastically as the doors close on her terrified face. The elevator starts its climb, normally floor 5, 6, 7

My sister demanded I gain weight back after I lost it for her wedding. So I'd always been the bigger sister. Megan was the pretty one with the perfect hair and the sorority friends. I was the funny one who made self deprecating jokes at family dinners. That's just how it was. We never really talked about it, but everyone knew the dynamic. When she got engaged to Mark last April, she pulled me aside at Mom's house right after everyone finished congratulating her. We were standing in the kitchen, and she had this concerned look on her face. She said, maybe I should think about getting healthier before the wedding. Not in a mean way, just like she was genuinely worried about me. Even offered to pay for this nutritionist in Denver named Patricia who'd helped her roommate lose 30 pounds. I was honestly touched. It felt like she actually cared. So I booked the appointment. Patricia was intense, but in a good way. She put me on this whole meal plan. Told me to start moving my body every day. Said it would change my life. I took it seriously. I started waking up at 5:00am for Crossfit at this place called Iron Valley near my apartment. The first week, I thought I was going to die. My legs were so sore, I had to hold onto the railing to go downstairs. But I kept going. Every Sunday, I'd meal prep in my tiny kitchen. Chicken and sweet Potatoes in those glass containers. Enough for the whole week. I'd never been disciplined about anything in my life, but something about this felt different. I wanted to prove I could do it. Eight months later, I was down 65 pounds. My face looked different in the mirror. My clothes didn't fit anymore in a good way. I went shopping and bought this emerald green dress from Nordstrom that actually hugged my waist instead of hiding it. When I tried it on in the dressing room, I literally teared up. I'd never felt pretty before. Megan's bridal shower was at the same country club where the wedding would be. I wore the green dress. I walked in. I swear to god, conversations just stopped mid sentence. Her fiance, Mark, was talking to his groomsmen, and he literally did a double take. His mouth actually opened a little. Her maid of honor, Jessica, came rushing up to me before I even set my purse down.

Oh, my god. Who's your trainer? You look incredible. She didn't even say congratulations or ask how I was doing. First. I could feel eyes on me as I walked toward the gift table. Megan's college friends were whispering. Her Aunt Linda kept staring. This weird energy filled the room that I couldn't quite lace. Ten minutes in, Megan appeared next to me and grabbed my wrist. Not hard, but firm. Hey, can we talk for a second? She was smiling, but her grip was tight. She pulled me toward the hallway that LED to the bathroom. Once we were alone, she dropped the smile. Okay, so you look amazing. Seriously, I'm so proud of you. But for the actual wedding, maybe wear something a little less attention grabbing, like that navy dress you wore to Easter. It's more elegant. I pulled my arm back slowly. Megan, you literally paid Patricia $200 to tell me to lose weight for your wedding. Her smile flickered like a candle in wind. Yeah, but I didn't think you'd go this hard. Like, people at the shower couldn't stop talking about you. They're gonna be looking at you instead of me at the wedding. Something cold settled in my stomach. So you wanted me to lose some weight, just not too much weight. That's not what I'm saying. I just think the navy dress would photograph at her with the wedding colors. I looked at her standing there in her white bridal shower dress. And I realized this had nothing to do with photography. I'm wearing the green dress, Megan. Her jaw tightened. Fine. Whatever. She walked back to the party without me. She didn't speak to me the rest of the shower. When I said goodbye, she gave me this tight little hug that lasted half a second. Wedding day came. I wore the green dress. I looked incredible, and I knew it. During photos, the photographer kept repositioning me toward the front of group shots. You've got great angles, he said. Mark's brother came up during cocktail.
